{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"181f413c-2520-414e-a76a-9c0d3ddd8fc3","content":"## What happened\n\n**DSA was obsoleted in .NET 7** (`SYSLIB0028`) and has been on a deprecation path since. macOS's native crypto frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) **never supported DSA** — .NET previously used an OpenSSL backend on macOS as a fallback. In .NET 11, that fallback was removed, so `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\nLinux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG) still have DSA support, which is why those platforms continue to work — for now.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify legacy signatures** (not create new ones), use **BouncyCastle**, which is a managed implementation with no OS dependency:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the built-in DSA verification:\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyDsaSignature(\n    byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] message, byte[] signature)\n{\n    var publicKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)\n        PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\n\n    var signer = new DsaSigner();\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n\n    // Decode the DER-encoded signature into (r, s)\n    var derSeq = (Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Sequence)\n        Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.Asn1Object.FromByteArray(signature);\n    var r = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)derSeq[0]).Value;\n    var s = ((Org.BouncyCastle.Asn1.DerInteger)derSeq[1]).Value;\n\n    // Hash the message with SHA-1 (typical for legacy DSA)\n    var digest = System.Security.Cryptography.SHA1.HashData(message);\n\n    return signer.VerifySignature(digest, r, s);\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- BouncyCastle is pure managed code — works identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS\n- Suppress the obsolete warning with `#pragma warning disable SYSLIB0028` if you still have any `System.Security.Cryptography.DSA` references during migration\n- For **new** signing needs, migrate to `ECDsa` or `RSA`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98c7f9f0-bd55-4cee-8395-24a4cb9c1ff9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) and the transition from .NET 10 to .NET 11, specifically on macOS. Let me think about what I know about this.\n\nThis is a known issue in the .NET ecosystem. Let me recall the details:\n\nIn .NET 7+, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically, DSA support on macOS has been a known issue because Apple's Security framework (and CommonCrypto/CryptoKit) dropped support for DSA. On Linux, DSA works through OpenSSL, and on Windows it works through CNG/CAPI.\n\n\nThe issue is that `DSA.Create()` throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because Apple removed DSA from their security frameworks. This has been the case since .NET Core, so the user's claim that it worked on .NET 10 is puzzling—I need to reconsider the timeline here. DSA was marked obsolete in .NET 7 with a warning, and on macOS it's always thrown `PlatformNotSupportedException` since Apple's native crypto frameworks never supported it. The real issue is that .NET on macOS historically relied on OpenSSL for DSA operations, but if .NET 11 removed that OpenSSL backend or changed how it handles crypto, DSA would stop working entirely on that platform. Since this is a hypothetical future scenario, the most likely explanation is that .NET 11 dropped the OpenSSL fallback for DSA on macOS that existed in earlier versions, leaving only Apple's native crypto APIs which never supported DSA. To work around this, I'd need to either use a third-party library like BouncyCastle for legacy DSA signature verification, or migrate to a modern algorithm like RSA or ECDsa.","outputTokens":1875,"requestId":"A464:111A97:22EBD2C:26A6DCE:6A03D901"},"id":"cadacc1c-0608-45